<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-320-548  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 320 548.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 29 1989 v6 n21 p73(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Miniscribe stock dives as Wall Street awaits revised forecast.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>March, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MiniScribe Corp. (finance).andO;Ticker:    MINY.andO;Topic:     Financial StabilityStockDisk DrivesWall StreetForecasting.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>While Wall Street waited for word on Miniscribe Corp.'s revised financialoutlook, the stock of the disk-drive maker remained at all-time low levelslast week.andM;The Longmont, Colo., company disclosed earlier this month that its financialstatements for fiscal years 1987 and 1988 are unreliable because of improperaccounting procedures.andM;Standard andamp; Poor's suspended its rating on $98 million of Miniscribe'ssubordinated debt in the wake of the disclosure.andP;  Moody's Investors ServiceInc. followed suit on May 22, downgrading its rating of Miniscribe'sconvertible subordinated debentures, which represent about $85 million of itsdebt.andM;According to the two Wall Street bond-rating firms, Miniscribe's current lackof accurate financial statements makes it impossible to accurately assess itsfinancial condition.andP;  Moody's also cited future technology changes in thedisk-drive market that could block Miniscribe's ability to regain financialhealth.andM;Investors responded by driving down Miniscribe's stock to a bid price of1-5/8 points on May 19.andP;  The stock recovered slightly, to 1-3/4 points on May23, but remained below its previous all-time low of 1-7/8 reached in August1985.andM;Miniscribe had reported a profit of $25.3 million on sales of $603.3 millionfor fiscal 1988; analysts say they expect that will turn into a loss.andP;  --andO;Richard  March</TEXT></DOC>